    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1627025888" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4627360426821634889">A really nice trick Schmitt presents us in this tiny little book: he lets a terminally ill boy experience every day he has left as if it were a decade, and in this way Oscar lives a &quot;full&quot; live. The candid tone of the little boy reminded me very much of the Little Prince by Exupery, including the wise-cracking and the fairy tale-atmosphere. Occasionally this results in very touching passages.<br/>But that&apos;s all for the positive remarks. I found the character of the Pink Lady too sugar sweet and the s</span>
  <span id="freeText4627360426821634889" style="display:none">A really nice trick Schmitt presents us in this tiny little book: he lets a terminally ill boy experience every day he has left as if it were a decade, and in this way Oscar lives a "full" live. The candid tone of the little boy reminded me very much of the Little Prince by Exupery, including the wise-cracking and the fairy tale-atmosphere. Occasionally this results in very touching passages.<br />But that's all for the positive remarks. I found the character of the Pink Lady too sugar sweet and the same goes for the wisdoms and religious truths that are sold on almost every page.<br />There is a striking parallel with "La vie devant Soi" by Romain Gary (published under the pseudonym Emile Ajar), which also has a 10-year-old boy under the care of an elderly Mme Rosa (coincidence? this book was published long before Schmitt's). But that book really is much more realistic and in-depth than that of Schmitt. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4627360426821634889" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


