<div id="review_569824090" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/569824090" />
    <a title="vaugnfreech" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18605478-vaugnfreech"><img alt="vaugnfreech" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1364159130p2/18605478.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/569824090?book_show_action=true">Mar 24, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="vaugnfreech" class="user" itemprop="url" name="vaugnfreech" href="/user/show/18605478-vaugnfreech">vaugnfreech</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18605478-vaugnfreech?shelf=general-fiction">general-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer569824090" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14850451630609562680">This is the second book in the back to back edition I bought by Eric-Emmanuel Schmitt. So Wikipedia says the books are part of the series Schmitt produced entitled The Cycle of Invisibles. Now that makes me want to read the others.<br/><br/>Oscar and the Lady in Pink is as good as Monsieur Ibrahim and the Flowers of the Koran. I noticed that the books have similar plots but differ in the philosophies (a kid learning much about life from an old person). In Oscar and the Lady in Pink, a ten year old boy nam</span>
  <span id="freeText14850451630609562680" style="display:none">This is the second book in the back to back edition I bought by Eric-Emmanuel Schmitt. So Wikipedia says the books are part of the series Schmitt produced entitled The Cycle of Invisibles. Now that makes me want to read the others.<br /><br />Oscar and the Lady in Pink is as good as Monsieur Ibrahim and the Flowers of the Koran. I noticed that the books have similar plots but differ in the philosophies (a kid learning much about life from an old person). In Oscar and the Lady in Pink, a ten year old boy named Oscar (who has leukemia) learns from an old woman named Mamie-Rose lessons about death, courage, love, and letting go of selfishness.<br /><br />Oscar is confined in a hospital and has undergone a bone marrow transplant...which somehow failed. So the book starts about his bitterness. Until Mamie-Rose advised him to write to God because it will a lot. So the whole book is a compilation of Oscar's letters. He tells about his friends: Bacon (a kid with burns), Popcorn (an obese kid), Einstein (a kid with hydrocephalus), and Peggy Blue (a girl with congenital heart problem). He tells about his frustration from his parents and with everyone in the hospital.<br /><br />Oscar and Mamie-Rose played this little game wherein Oscar would think that everyday of his life is equivalent to ten years...for the last 12 days of his life. And with it, Oscar grew as a man being just a kid. He experienced adolescence, midlife crisis, and eventually old age. And every time he shares to Mamie-Rose the things that burdened him, Mamie-Rose would tell him stories about her past wrestling career to inspire him and give him courage to move on.<br /><br />Honestly, the book is very very heartbreaking. Schmitt wrote it in the funniest way but as a reader, you can never escape the sadness you anticipated. The book explains much about death and what comes after it. It reminds me of reading Embraced by the Light by Beatie Eddie.<br /><br />The book is as short as Monsieur Ibrahim and the Flowers of the Koran. And still it makes me wonder how Schmitt could write such short complex of a book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14850451630609562680" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

